758
01:11:52,643 --> 01:12:03,391
which is a common speed limit in urban and residential areas, it may not seem like you're going that fast, but you are going about twice as fast as an average person can run.

759
01:12:04,412 --> 01:12:11,497
Record-setting Olympic runners have managed to reach speed limits around 25 miles per hour, but that is rare.

760
01:12:12,838 --> 01:12:14,179
A hypothetical situation.

761
01:12:14,779 --> 01:12:19,563
A vehicle is traveling 25 miles an hour, and a pedestrian enters the roadway.

762
01:12:20,344 --> 01:12:28,132
It takes two seconds for the driver to see the pedestrian, decide to stop the vehicle, and then press the brake.

763
01:12:29,013 --> 01:12:36,702
That means that before the driver has time to react, the car has continued moving 25 miles an hour for two whole seconds.

764
01:12:37,342 --> 01:12:41,547
The vehicle has moved 55 feet before they can even press the brake.

765
01:12:42,383 --> 01:12:55,113
If the car has an average stopping distance at 25 miles an hour of 30 feet, that means the car will have moved a total of 85 feet down the roadway before it comes to a stop.

766
01:12:56,314 --> 01:13:01,078
That is the length of eight Toyota Camrys, to put it into perspective, parked end to end.

767
01:13:02,719 --> 01:13:07,904
Because of the human factor, as speed increases, the stopping distance increases dramatically.

768
01:13:08,584 --> 01:13:12,007
At 30 miles per hour, which is our current default limit,

769
01:13:12,411 --> 01:13:14,212
The stopping distance is much greater.

770
01:13:14,232 --> 01:13:14,813
It's 109 feet.

771
01:13:14,833 --> 01:13:15,994
At 35 miles per hour, it goes up to 136 feet.

772
01:13:16,674 --> 01:13:18,196
And you're not really speeding yet.

773
01:13:24,320 --> 01:13:32,647
switch up the numbers to a freeway speed, which is roughly 60 miles per hour, and the stopping distance is about 305 feet.

774
01:13:33,267 --> 01:13:35,689
